# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ipsec
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] In computing, **Internet Protocol Security** (**IPsec**) is a secure network protocol suite that authenticates and encrypts packets of data to provide secure encrypted communication between two computers over an Internet Protocol network.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] It is used in virtual private networks (VPNs).
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] IPsec includes protocols for establishing mutual authentication between agents at the beginning of a session and negotiation of cryptographic keys to use during the session.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] IPsec can protect data flows between a pair of hosts (*host-to-host*), between a pair of security gateways (*network-to-network*), or between a security gateway and a host (*network-to-host*).
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] IPsec uses cryptographic security services to protect communications over Internet Protocol (IP) networks.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] It supports network-level peer authentication, data origin authentication, data integrity, data confidentiality (encryption), and protection from replay attacks.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] Starting in the early 1970s, the Advanced Research Projects Agency sponsored a series of experimental ARPANET encryption devices, at first for native ARPANET packet encryption and subsequently for TCP/IP packet encryption; some of these were certified and fielded.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] From 1986 to 1991, the NSA sponsored the development of security protocols for the Internet under its Secure Data Network Systems (SDNS) program.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] This brought together various vendors including Motorola who produced a network encryption device in 1988.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] The work was openly published from about 1988 by NIST and, of these, *Security Protocol at Layer 3* (SP3) would eventually morph into the ISO standard Network Layer Security Protocol (NLSP).
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] In 1992, the US Naval Research Laboratory (NRL) was funded by DARPA CSTO to implement IPv6 and to research and implement IP encryption in 4.4 BSD, supporting both SPARC and x86 CPU architectures.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] DARPA made its implementation freely available via MIT.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] Under NRL's DARPA-funded research effort, NRL developed the IETF standards-track specifications (RFC 1825 through RFC 1827) for IPsec.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] NRL's IPsec implementation was described in their paper in the 1996 USENIX Conference Proceedings.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] NRL's open-source IPsec implementation was made available online by MIT and became the basis for most initial commercial implementations.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] The Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) formed the IP Security Working Group in 1992 to standardize openly specified security extensions to IP, called *IPsec*.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] The NRL developed standards were published by the IETF as RFC 1825 through RFC 1827.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] The initial IPv4 suite was developed with few security provisions.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] As a part of the IPv4 enhancement, IPsec is a layer 3 OSI model or internet layer end-to-end security scheme.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] The Security Authentication Header (AH) was developed at the US Naval Research Laboratory in the early 1990s and is derived in part from previous IETF standards' work for authentication of the Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP) version 2.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] Authentication Header (AH) is a member of the IPsec protocol suite.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] AH ensures connectionless integrity by using a hash function and a secret shared key in the AH algorithm.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] AH also guarantees the data origin by authenticating IP packets.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] Optionally a sequence number can protect the IPsec packet's contents against replay attacks, using the sliding window technique and discarding old packets.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] AH operates directly on top of IP, using IP protocol number 51.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] Type of the next header, indicating what upper-layer protocol was protected.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] For example, an AH value of 4 equals 3×(32-bit fixed-length AH fields) + 3×(32-bit ICV fields) − 2 and thus an AH value of 4 means 24 octets.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] Although the size is measured in 4-octet units, the length of this header needs to be a multiple of 8 octets if carried in an IPv6 packet.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] Reserved for future use (all zeroes until then).
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] When replay detection is enabled, sequence numbers are never reused, because a new security association must be renegotiated before an attempt to increment the sequence number beyond its maximum value.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] The IP Encapsulating Security Payload (ESP) was developed at the Naval Research Laboratory starting in 1992 as part of a DARPA-sponsored research project, and was openly published by IETF SIPP Working Group drafted in December 1993 as a security extension for SIPP.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] This ESP was originally derived from the US Department of Defense SP3D protocol, rather than being derived from the ISO Network-Layer Security Protocol (NLSP).
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] The SP3D protocol specification was published by NIST in the late 1980s, but designed by the Secure Data Network System project of the US Department of Defense.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] Encapsulating Security Payload (ESP) is a member of the IPsec protocol suite.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] It provides origin authenticity through source authentication, data integrity through hash functions and confidentiality through encryption protection for IP packets.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] ESP also supports encryption-only and authentication-only configurations, but using encryption without authentication is strongly discouraged because it is insecure.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] Unlike Authentication Header (AH), ESP in transport mode does not provide integrity and authentication for the entire IP packet.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] However, in tunnel mode, where the entire original IP packet is encapsulated with a new packet header added, ESP protection is afforded to the whole inner IP packet (including the inner header) while the outer header (including any outer IPv4 options or IPv6 extension headers) remains unprotected.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] ESP operates directly on top of IP, using IP protocol number 50.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] There is a separate counter kept for every security association.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] The protected contents of the original IP packet, including any data used to protect the contents (e.g. an Initialisation Vector for the cryptographic algorithm).
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] ) is used for dummy packets, which may be inserted in the stream, and which contents should be discarded.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] The IPsec protocols use a security association, where the communicating parties establish shared security attributes such as algorithms and keys.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] As such, IPsec provides a range of options once it has been determined whether AH or ESP is used.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] Before exchanging data, the two hosts agree on which symmetric encryption algorithm is used to encrypt the IP packet, for example AES or ChaCha20, and which hash function is used to ensure the integrity of the data, such as BLAKE2 or SHA256.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] These parameters are agreed for the particular session, for which a lifetime must be agreed and a session key.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] The algorithm for authentication is also agreed before the data transfer takes place and IPsec supports a range of methods.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] Authentication is possible through pre-shared key, where a symmetric key is already in the possession of both hosts, and the hosts send each other hashes of the shared key to prove that they are in possession of the same key.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] IPsec also supports public key encryption, where each host has a public and a private key, they exchange their public keys and each host sends the other a nonce encrypted with the other host's public key.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] Alternatively if both hosts hold a public key certificate from a certificate authority, this can be used for IPsec authentication.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] The security associations of IPsec are established using the Internet Security Association and Key Management Protocol (ISAKMP).
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] ISAKMP is implemented by manual configuration with pre-shared secrets, Internet Key Exchange (IKE and IKEv2), Kerberized Internet Negotiation of Keys (KINK), and the use of IPSECKEY DNS records.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] RFC 5386 defines Better-Than-Nothing Security (BTNS) as an unauthenticated mode of IPsec using an extended IKE protocol.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] Cremers, and others have used formal methods to identify various anomalies which exist in IKEv1 and also in IKEv2.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] A similar procedure is performed for an incoming packet, where IPsec gathers decryption and verification keys from the security association database.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] For IP multicast a security association is provided for the group, and is duplicated across all authorized receivers of the group.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] There may be more than one security association for a group, using different SPIs, thereby allowing multiple levels and sets of security within a group.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] Indeed, each sender can have multiple security associations, allowing authentication, since a receiver can only know that someone knowing the keys sent the data.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] Note that the relevant standard does not describe how the association is chosen and duplicated across the group; it is assumed that a responsible party will have made the choice.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] To ensure that the connection between two endpoints has not been interrupted, endpoints exchange keepalive messages at regular intervals, which can also be used to automatically reestablish a tunnel lost due to connection interruption.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] Dead Peer Detection (DPD) is a method of detecting a dead Internet Key Exchange (IKE) peer.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] The method uses IPsec traffic patterns to minimize the number of messages required to confirm the availability of a peer.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] DPD is used to reclaim the lost resources in case a peer is found dead and it is also used to perform IKE peer failover.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] The IPsec protocols AH and ESP can be implemented in a host-to-host transport mode, as well as in a network tunneling mode.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] In transport mode, only the payload of the IP packet is usually encrypted or authenticated.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] The routing is intact, since the IP header is neither modified nor encrypted; however, when the authentication header is used, the IP addresses cannot be modified by network address translation, as this always invalidates the hash value.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] The transport and application layers are always secured by a hash, so they cannot be modified in any way, for example by translating the port numbers.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] A means to encapsulate IPsec messages for NAT traversal (NAT-T) has been defined by RFC documents describing the NAT-T mechanism.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] In tunnel mode, the entire IP packet is encrypted and authenticated.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] It is then encapsulated into a new IP packet with a new IP header.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] Tunnel mode is used to create virtual private networks for network-to-network communications (e.g. between routers to link sites), host-to-network communications (e.g. remote user access) and host-to-host communications (e.g. private chat).
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] The IPsec can be implemented in the IP stack of an operating system.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] This method of implementation is done for hosts and security gateways.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] Various IPsec capable IP stacks are available from companies, such as HP or IBM.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] An alternative is so called bump-in-the-stack (BITS) implementation, where the operating system source code does not have to be modified.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] Here IPsec is installed between the IP stack and the network drivers.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] This way operating systems can be retrofitted with IPsec.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] This method of implementation is also used for both hosts and gateways.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] However, when retrofitting IPsec the encapsulation of IP packets may cause problems for the automatic path MTU discovery, where the maximum transmission unit (MTU) size on the network path between two IP hosts is established.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] If a host or gateway has a separate cryptoprocessor, which is common in the military and can also be found in commercial systems, a so-called bump-in-the-wire (BITW) implementation of IPsec is possible.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] When IPsec is implemented in the kernel, the key management and ISAKMP/IKE negotiation is carried out from user space.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] The NRL-developed and openly specified "PF_KEY Key Management API, Version 2" is often used to enable the application-space key management application to update the IPsec security associations stored within the kernel-space IPsec implementation.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] Existing IPsec implementations usually include ESP, AH, and IKE version 2.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] Existing IPsec implementations on Unix-like operating systems, for example, Solaris or Linux, usually include PF_KEY version 2.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] Embedded IPsec can be used to ensure the secure communication among applications running over constrained resource systems with a small overhead.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] IPsec was developed in conjunction with IPv6 and was originally required to be supported by all standards-compliant implementations of IPv6 before RFC 6434 made it only a recommendation.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] IPsec is also optional for IPv4 implementations.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] IPsec is most commonly used to secure IPv4 traffic.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] IPsec protocols were originally defined in RFC 1825 through RFC 1829, which were published in 1995.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] In 1998, these documents were superseded by RFC 2401 and RFC 2412 with a few incompatible engineering details, although they were conceptually identical.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] In addition, a mutual authentication and key exchange protocol Internet Key Exchange (IKE) was defined to create and manage security associations.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] In December 2005, new standards were defined in RFC 4301 and RFC 4309 which are largely a superset of the previous editions with a second version of the Internet Key Exchange standard IKEv2.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] These third-generation documents standardized the abbreviation of IPsec to uppercase "IP" and lowercase "sec".
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] "ESP" generally refers to RFC 4303, which is the most recent version of the specification.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] Since mid-2008, an IPsec Maintenance and Extensions (ipsecme) working group is active at the IETF.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] In 2013, as part of the Snowden leaks, it was revealed that the US National Security Agency had been actively working to "Insert vulnerabilities into commercial encryption systems, IT systems, networks, and endpoint communications devices used by targets" as part of the Bullrun program.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] There are allegations that IPsec was a targeted encryption system.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] The OpenBSD IPsec stack came later on and also was widely copied.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] In a letter which OpenBSD lead developer Theo de Raadt received on 11 Dec 2010 from Gregory Perry, it is alleged that Jason Wright and others, working for the FBI, inserted "a number of backdoors and side channel key leaking mechanisms" into the OpenBSD crypto code.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] In the forwarded email from 2010, Theo de Raadt did not at first express an official position on the validity of the claims, apart from the implicit endorsement from forwarding the email.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] Jason Wright's response to the allegations: "Every urban legend is made more real by the inclusion of real names, dates, and times.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] Gregory Perry's email falls into this category. ...
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] I will state clearly that I did not add backdoors to the OpenBSD operating system or the OpenBSD Cryptographic Framework (OCF)." Some days later, de Raadt commented that "I believe that NETSEC was probably contracted to write backdoors as alleged. ...
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] If those were written, I don't believe they made it into our tree." This was published before the Snowden leaks.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] An alternative explanation put forward by the authors of the Logjam attack suggests that the NSA compromised IPsec VPNs by undermining the Diffie-Hellman algorithm used in the key exchange.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] In their paper, they allege the NSA specially built a computing cluster to precompute multiplicative subgroups for specific primes and generators, such as for the second Oakley group defined in RFC 2409.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] As of May 2015, 90% of addressable IPsec VPNs supported the second Oakley group as part of IKE.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] If an organization were to precompute this group, they could derive the keys being exchanged and decrypt traffic without inserting any software backdoors.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] The Cisco PIX and ASA firewalls had vulnerabilities that were used for wiretapping by the NSA.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] Furthermore, IPsec VPNs using "Aggressive Mode" settings send a hash of the PSK in the clear.
[src:ipsec/encapsulating-security-payload] This can be and apparently is targeted by the NSA using offline dictionary attacks.
[src:ipsec/internet-key-exchange] In computing, **Internet Key Exchange** (**IKE**, versioned as **IKEv1** and **IKEv2**) is the protocol used to set up a security association (SA) in the IPsec protocol suite.
[src:ipsec/internet-key-exchange] IKE builds upon the Oakley protocol and ISAKMP.
[src:ipsec/internet-key-exchange] IKE uses X.509 certificates for authentication ‒ either pre-shared or distributed using DNS (preferably with DNSSEC) ‒ and a Diffie–Hellman key exchange to set up a shared session secret from which cryptographic keys are derived.
[src:ipsec/internet-key-exchange] A IETF draft is currently being written to provide a quantum-resistant key establishment using ML-KEM.
[src:ipsec/internet-key-exchange] In addition, a security policy for every peer which will connect must be manually maintained.
[src:ipsec/internet-key-exchange] RFC 4306 updated IKE to version two (IKEv2) in December 2005.
[src:ipsec/internet-key-exchange] RFC 4718 clarified some open details in October 2006.
[src:ipsec/internet-key-exchange] RFC 5996 combined these two documents plus additional clarifications into the updated IKEv2, published in September 2010.
[src:ipsec/internet-key-exchange] A later update upgraded the document from Proposed Standard to Internet Standard, published as RFC 7296 in October 2014.
[src:ipsec/internet-key-exchange] The parent organization of the IETF, the Internet Society (ISOC), has maintained the copyrights of these standards as freely available to the Internet community.
[src:ipsec/internet-key-exchange] Most IPsec implementations consist of an IKE daemon that runs in user space and an IPsec stack in the kernel that processes the actual IP packets.
[src:ipsec/internet-key-exchange] User-space daemons have easy access to mass storage containing configuration information, such as the IPsec endpoint addresses, keys and certificates, as required.
[src:ipsec/internet-key-exchange] Kernel modules, on the other hand, can process packets efficiently and with minimum overhead—which is important for performance reasons.
[src:ipsec/internet-key-exchange] The IKE protocol uses UDP packets, usually on port 500, and generally requires 4–6 packets with 2–3 round trips to create an ISAKMP security association (SA) on both sides.
[src:ipsec/internet-key-exchange] The negotiated key material is then given to the IPsec stack.
[src:ipsec/internet-key-exchange] For instance, this could be an AES key, information identifying the IP endpoints and ports that are to be protected, as well as what type of IPsec tunnel has been created.
[src:ipsec/internet-key-exchange] The IPsec stack, in turn, intercepts the relevant IP packets if and where appropriate and performs encryption/decryption as required.
[src:ipsec/internet-key-exchange] Implementations vary on how the interception of the packets is done—for example, some use virtual devices, others take a slice out of the firewall, etc.
[src:ipsec/internet-key-exchange] IKEv1 consists of two phases: phase 1 and phase 2.
[src:ipsec/internet-key-exchange] IKE phase one's purpose is to establish a secure authenticated communication channel by using the Diffie–Hellman key exchange algorithm to generate a shared secret key to encrypt further IKE communications.
[src:ipsec/internet-key-exchange] This negotiation results in one single bi-directional ISAKMP security association.
[src:ipsec/internet-key-exchange] The authentication can be performed using either pre-shared key (shared secret), signatures, or public key encryption.
[src:ipsec/internet-key-exchange] Phase 1 operates in either Main Mode or Aggressive Mode.
[src:ipsec/internet-key-exchange] Main Mode protects the identity of the peers and the hash of the shared key by encrypting them; Aggressive Mode does not.
[src:ipsec/internet-key-exchange] During IKE phase two, the IKE peers use the secure channel established in Phase 1 to negotiate Security Associations on behalf of other services like IPsec.
[src:ipsec/internet-key-exchange] The negotiation results in a minimum of two unidirectional security associations (one inbound and one outbound).
[src:ipsec/internet-key-exchange] Originally, IKE had numerous configuration options but lacked a general facility for automatic negotiation of a universally supported default case.
[src:ipsec/internet-key-exchange] As a result, both endpoints needed to exactly agree on every parameter of the security association—such as encryption algorithms, key exchange methods, and lifetimes—or the connection would fail.
[src:ipsec/internet-key-exchange] This led to frequent interoperability issues between different vendors' implementations.
[src:ipsec/internet-key-exchange] Troubleshooting was further complicated by limited or cryptic debug output in many implementations.
[src:ipsec/internet-key-exchange] The IKEv1 specifications also permitted a significant degree of interpretation, sometimes bordering on design flaws.
[src:ipsec/internet-key-exchange] One example is Dead Peer Detection (DPD), which was implemented inconsistently across vendors.
[src:ipsec/internet-key-exchange] Even with correctly matched configurations, this could result in negotiation failures or dropped tunnels.
[src:ipsec/internet-key-exchange] The IKEv2 protocol was described in Appendix A of RFC 4306 in 2005.
[src:ipsec/internet-key-exchange] This is to ensure that the initiator is really capable of handling an IKE response from the responder.
[src:ipsec/internet-key-exchange] The IETF ipsecme working group has standardized a number of extensions, with the goal of modernizing the IKEv2 protocol and adapting it better to high volume, production environments.
[src:ipsec/internet-key-exchange] IKE is supported as part of the IPsec implementation in Windows 2000, Windows XP, Windows Server 2003, Windows Vista and Windows Server 2008.
[src:ipsec/internet-key-exchange] The ISAKMP/IKE implementation was jointly developed by Cisco and Microsoft.
[src:ipsec/internet-key-exchange] Microsoft Windows 7 and Windows Server 2008 R2 partially support IKEv2 (RFC 7296) as well as MOBIKE (RFC 4555) through the *VPN Reconnect* feature (also known as *Agile VPN*).
[src:ipsec/internet-key-exchange] There are several open source implementations of IPsec with associated IKE capabilities.
[src:ipsec/internet-key-exchange] On Linux, Libreswan, Openswan and strongSwan implementations provide an IKE daemon which can configure (i.e., establish SAs) to the KLIPS or XFRM/NETKEY kernel-based IPsec stacks.
[src:ipsec/internet-key-exchange] XFRM/NETKEY is the Linux native IPsec implementation available as of version 2.6.
[src:ipsec/internet-key-exchange] The Berkeley Software Distributions also implements IPsec, IKE daemon via the OpenBSD Cryptographic Framework (OCF), which makes supporting cryptographic accelerators much easier.
[src:ipsec/internet-key-exchange] A number of network equipment vendors have created their own IKE daemons (and IPsec implementations), or license a stack from one another.
[src:ipsec/internet-key-exchange] There are a number of implementations of IKEv2 and some of the companies dealing in IPsec certification and interoperability testing are starting to hold workshops for testing as well as updated certification requirements to deal with IKEv2 testing.
[src:ipsec/internet-key-exchange] Leaked NSA presentations released in 2014 by *Der Spiegel* indicate that IKE is being exploited in an unknown manner to decrypt IPsec traffic, as is ISAKMP.
[src:ipsec/internet-key-exchange] The researchers who discovered the Logjam attack state that breaking a 1024-bit Diffie–Hellman group would break 66% of VPN servers, 18% of the top million HTTPS domains, and 26% of SSH servers, which the researchers claim is consistent with the leaks.
[src:ipsec/internet-key-exchange] This claim was refuted in 2015 by both Eyal Ronen and Adi Shamir in their paper "Critical Review of Imperfect Forward Secrecy" and by Paul Wouters of Libreswan in a 2015 article "66% of VPN's [*sic*] are not in fact broken".
[src:ipsec/internet-key-exchange] IPsec VPN configurations which allow for negotiation of multiple configurations are subject to MITM-based downgrade attacks between the offered configurations, with both IKEv1 and IKEv2.
[src:ipsec/internet-key-exchange] This can be avoided by careful segregation of client systems onto multiple service access points with stricter configurations.
[src:ipsec/internet-key-exchange] Both versions of the IKE standard are susceptible to an offline dictionary attack when a low entropy password is used.
[src:ipsec/internet-key-exchange] For the IKEv1 this is true for main mode and aggressive mode.
[src:ipsec/security-association] A **security association** (**SA**) is the establishment of shared security attributes between two network entities to support secure communication.
[src:ipsec/security-association] An SA may include attributes such as: cryptographic algorithm and mode; traffic encryption key; and parameters for the network data to be passed over the connection.
[src:ipsec/security-association] The framework for establishing security associations is provided by the Internet Security Association and Key Management Protocol (ISAKMP).
[src:ipsec/security-association] Protocols such as Internet Key Exchange (IKE) and Kerberized Internet Negotiation of Keys (KINK) provide authenticated keying material.
[src:ipsec/security-association] An SA is a simplex (one-way channel) and logical connection which endorses and provides a secure data connection between the network devices.
[src:ipsec/security-association] The fundamental requirement of an SA arrives when the two entities communicate over more than one channel.
[src:ipsec/security-association] Take, for example, a mobile subscriber and a base station.
[src:ipsec/security-association] The subscriber may subscribe itself to more than one service.
[src:ipsec/security-association] Therefore, each service may have different service primitives, such as a data encryption algorithm, public key, or initialization vector.
[src:ipsec/security-association] To make things easier, all of this security information is grouped logically, and the logical group itself is a Security Association.
[src:ipsec/security-association] So both the base station and mobile subscriber will share the SAID, and they will derive all the security parameters.
[src:ipsec/security-association] In other words, an SA is a logical group of security parameters that enable the sharing of information to another entity.
